<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-06T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-06T13:00:00-05:00" n="449" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d449">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00Sonora/533: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Nogales</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Damm</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nogales, Ariz</hi></placeName>., <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-06T12:00:00-06:00">April 6,
                                1929—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 4:43 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>From Vice Consul, Ciudad Obregon:</p>
                        <p>April 5, 9 p.m. The rebel army retreated from Culiacán to San Bias
                            yesterday where temporary headquarters were established. Seven troop
                            trains carrying approximately 500 troops were used. District <pb facs="0505" n="387" xml:id="pg_387"/> through which crossing passes
                            is being looted and forced loans levied irrespective of nationality.
                            Citizens of Los Mochis were compelled to pay 100,000 pesos. Conferred
                            with Commander Comerford of the destroyer <hi rend="italic">Robert
                                Smith</hi> today making arrangements for the protection of American
                            lives in case of necessity.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Damm</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>